column29:
As the NAR lost the litigation against Rhonda Burnett and others, it has become clear that the US real estate system, refined over 100 years and once considered the best on the planet (a perspective I hold from my experience in real estate across three continents), is undergoing a significant change. It appears to be shifting towards a more European and South American model, which many perceive as less efficient, leaving buyers to navigate the process largely on their own.
 

 Sellers may initially celebrate this change, but they may soon realize that selling their properties could take longer and require them to lower prices by 5-10% to attract buyers. Additionally, when these sellers become buyers themselves, they may miss the support of the 1.6 million enthusiastic and well-prepared agents who previously helped them find homes at no cost.
 

 The perceived savings of 3% in commission fees may ultimately be offset by the less efficient processes that now come into play. It is disheartening to witness what appears

Her main frustration was that she wasn't prepared for the amount of manual setup required before fully using Sierra. For example, coming from Boomtown, she expected pre-built Action Plans and Drip Campaigns that she could use immediately. She was surprised to learn that she would need to pay for services like Bludoor or GGMS to access these features. Karssen also expressed concerns about the additional costs of running Google Ads, which she didn’t expect. She mentioned being unprepared to have to watch training videos or read through email instructions to get answers to her questions. Additionally, she was disappointed to hear about the lag period before seeing consistent lead generation results.
 However, her biggest issue is manually adding customized, saved searches to her 1,900+ leads individually. Rick and I discussed strategies with her, such as bulk applying generalized E-alerts to improve lead engagement. She was also frustrated that some of her E-alerts were not being delivered.
